  "school": "Price Action",
  "definition": "A shallow, slow counter-trend move following an impulsive expansion leg, where price pulls back into a prior point of interest (e.g., fair value gap, order block, PD array) before resuming the prevailing trend. It forms a protected swing and acts as a continuation signature, providing entry opportunities aligned with the dominant order flow.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Confirm a prior impulsive expansion move in a trending direction.",
    "Observe a counter-trend pullback that is shallow, slow, and composed of small-ranged candles, typically taking more time than the expansion leg.",
    "Price must pull back into a defined point of interest such as a fair value gap, order block, PD array, or the 50% equilibrium of the prior expansion candle.",
    "The pullback respects the point of interest: bodies do not close beyond it, price remains in the upper (bullish) or lower (bearish) half without breaking the prior structural swing high/low.",
    "Look for a liquidity sweep (inducement) of a minor opposing high/low within the point of interest, often preceding continuation.",
    "Confirmation of the retracement end requires a swift closure (often V-shaped) through the series of opposing candles, producing a change in state of delivery and forming a protected swing.",
    "Distinguish from reversal: absence of aggressive opposing expansion and no close beyond the structural swing.",
    "Distinguish from consolidation: retracement is directional, forms a protected swing; sideways or slow multi-candle closures indicate consolidation.",
    "Disqualify the move as a simple retracement if price closes beyond the 50% equilibrium of the prior expansion, if multiple expansion candles have already occurred, or if a higher-timeframe target has been reached.",
    "Multi-timeframe verification: retracement direction on lower timeframe should align with higher timeframe bias."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Retracements are continuation signatures used to enter with the prevailing trend at a favorable price. After expansion, wait for a shallow pullback into a point of interest (e.g., fair value gap, order block). Once price closes through the opposing candles, forming a protected swing with a change in state of delivery, enter in the trend direction. Place stops beyond the protected swing and target prior liquidity (failure swings, equal highs/lows) aiming for at least 2R. Align with higher-timeframe bias and avoid entries after multiple expansion legs or when objectives are reached.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Entering too early: before a confirmed protected swing forms, before a liquidity sweep (inducement), or without lower-timeframe confirmation (closure through opposing candles, change in state of delivery).",
    "Confusing a retracement with a reversal: misinterpreting aggressive opposing candles or a break of structural swing/equilibrium as a retracement, leading to counter-trend trades.",
    "Confusing a retracement with consolidation: failing to distinguish a directional pullback that forms a protected swing from sideways oscillation or slow multi-candle closures without a clean swing.",
    "Expecting deep pullbacks during strong expansion: anticipating price will reach discount/premium or deep into fair value gaps when shallow retracements are the norm.",
    "Chasing the initial expansion or entering without a defined point of interest (fair value gap, order block, etc.).",
    "Taking retracement entries after the higher-timeframe objective has been hit or after multiple consecutive expansion candles, when a new phase of price is more likely.",
    "Using incorrect equilibrium measurements (e.g., full candle range instead of wick-to-wick 50%) or entering without at least 2R risk-to-reward.",
    "Neglecting higher-timeframe bias and overall market context (e.g., entering at random times without aligning to the prevailing daily/weekly direction).",
    "Confusing 'expansion meets expansion' (bearish signal) with 'expansion meets retracement' (bullish continuation).",
    "Not waiting for daily close to confirm retracement vs reversal, leading to intraday misjudgment."
  ],
